    <h1>Logic Blocks 1 Exercise</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p><strong>Objective:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>Create an Action Block for the Products table</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Context:&nbsp;</strong>For tables that are highly transactional =
or will have transactions created from several sources (internal and extern=
al) it can make sense to create an Action Block. By creating one, the LB ca=
n be called by other logic blocks. If an Action Block is not created, the s=
ources will insert or update directly and validations occur at the trigger =
level.</p>
<p>In this exercise, we are assuming that products are created from many di=
fferent sources. You could have an external product or another product modu=
le that handles R&amp;D type activities that lead to products being created=
. The logic block is simple, but if the Products application expanded, the =
action block would be more involved and potentially modify values that are =
passed in before doing an update. As this is a simpler implementation, the =
LB updates with whatever values are passed in.</p>
